      <h2>Garden Grove heritage — CMA's SoCal installed base</h2>
      <p>
        Before Ali Group acquired CMA in 2004 and consolidated manufacturing to Winston-Salem, CMA was a Garden
        Grove, California manufacturer. That SoCal-local heritage is the reason LA has a thicker CMA installed base
        than most American markets. Long-tenure restaurants from Brentwood to Long Beach, mid-century hotel
        properties in Santa Monica and the Valley, and older institutional kitchens across the LA basin are running
        CMA units that were installed in the 80s and 90s when CMA was making equipment 25 miles away in Orange
        County.
      </p>
      <p>
        Those Garden Grove-era CMA units are still serviceable. Ali Group's parts discipline means even 30-year-old
        CMA door machines can get common parts through the Winston-Salem channel, and the 80s-era units are
        mechanically simpler than current production — direct wash pump, mechanical timer, straightforward
        thermostat control. For an operator running a Garden Grove-era CMA that's been in service for 25+ years,
        repair is almost always the sensible call unless the wash tank itself has corroded or the frame structure
        has failed.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section alt">
    <div class="wrap narrow">
      <h2>California Energy Commission rebates and Energy Mizer</h2>
      <p>
        Energy Mizer is CMA's ENERGY STAR product line — the door machines configured for reduced water consumption
        (typically 1.0 gallons per rack or less) and optional heat-recovery that captures exhaust heat to preheat
        incoming fill water. ENERGY STAR qualification is the gateway to California Energy Commission commercial
        foodservice rebates, plus LADWP and Southern California Edison commercial rebate programs when those
        programs have active funding.
      </p>
      <p>
        For LA operators considering Energy Mizer over the EVA-Series non-ENERGY STAR equivalent, the math usually
        works in ENERGY STAR's favor once you factor in the rebate plus the lifecycle water savings. Rebate amounts
        change — check current status at cec.ca.gov or through your utility's commercial program — but the Energy
        Mizer qualifies for the full rebate where rebate programs are active. We can advise on Energy Mizer-specific
        maintenance that preserves the ENERGY STAR performance (heat-recovery module cleaning, calibration of
        water-conservation sensors) during service calls.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

